To create the described diagrams using TikZ, we need to generate two plots: one for the 2D map of the mixing function and another for the extension of the ASO component over the selected region. Below is the LaTeX code to achieve these plots:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5mm]{standalone}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.16}

\begin{document}

% Plot (a): 2D map of the mixing function
\begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
        width=8cm,
        height=6cm,
        xlabel=$\varpi$,
        ylabel=$z$,
        zlabel=$f(\varpi, z)$,
        colormap={mix}{
            rgb(0cm)=(blue);
            rgb(1cm)=(red)
        },
        view={45}{30},
        domain=0:2*pi,
        y domain=-1:1,
        samples=100,
        surf,
        z buffer=sort,
        opacity=0.7,
        colorbar
    ]
        \addplot3[surf] {sin(x)*cos(y)};
    \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

% Plot (b): Extension of the ASO component over the selected region
\begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
        width=8cm,
        height=6cm,
        xlabel=$x$,
        ylabel=$y$,
        zlabel=$f(x, y)$,
        colormap={mix}{
            rgb(0cm)=(blue);
            rgb(1cm)=(red)
        },
        view={45}{30},
        domain=-1:1,
        y domain=-1:1,
        samples=100,
        surf,
        z buffer=sort,
        opacity=0.7,
        colorbar
    ]
        \addplot3[surf] {exp(-x^2 - y^2)};
    \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

